  "prompt": "What is the value of [math]\\sqrt [i\\pi ] {-1}[/math]?",
  "response": "To solve for \\(\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1}\\), we can express \\(-1\\) in exponential form using Euler's formula. The complex number \\(-1\\) can be represented as:\n\n\\[\n-1 = e^{i\\pi}\n\\]\n\nNow, we want to find \\(\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1}\\). This can be rewritten using the exponential form:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1} = (-1)^{\\frac{1}{i\\pi}}\n\\]\n\nSubstituting the exponential representation of \\(-1\\):\n\n\\[\n(-1)^{\\frac{1}{i\\pi}} = \\left(e^{i\\pi}\\right)^{\\frac{1}{i\\pi}} = e^{\\frac{i\\pi}{i\\pi}} = e^1 = e\n\\]\n\nThus, we find that:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1} = e\n\\]\n\nThe value of \\(\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1}\\) is \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{e}\n\\]",
